AB  - This chapter addresses policy and practice considerations with a view to reducing cyberbullying and enhancing digital citizenship. I highlight the policy vacuum and challenges of balancing free expression, safety, privacy, supervision and regulation within the school context. I explain the emerging pattern in my research, that suggests digital natives (youth growing up immersed in digital media) often fail to distinguish the lines between harmless joking or teasing, and harmful cyberbullying that negatively impacts those targeted and fail to realize potential legal risks. Legal liability for cyberbullying can include lawsuits for defamation through online postings that spread rumours, gossip and demeaning comments. Young people risk criminal liability for online threats made in jest that might be perceived as "actual" threats that will be carried out in physical contexts. Potential charges of possession and distribution of child pornography can be laid for "sexting," a form of intimate photographs or videotapes distributed online to embarrass others. My chapter calls for legal literacy among educators, and the need to sensitize the legal community to shifting norms of social communication among digital youth. I argue that new laws specifically aimed at controlling cyberbullying show less promise than legal frameworks in North America, Europe and Australia that already exist. These frameworks include constitutional and human rights considerations, tort law (civil liability - defamation, libel, slander, privacy); and criminal law. I argue for preventative policy and practice responses that are congruent with the obligations of countries that are parties to the International Convention on the Rights of the Child (CRC). These approaches will go further towards mobilizing socially responsible digital citizenship among youth than reactive approaches that continue to be adopted by schools and some governments that are introducing harsher legislation. © 2013 Nova Scie