AB  - While the ease at which capital crosses international borders has been well treated within the globalization literature, there has been relatively little discussion of the other main component of global economic activity-labor. Labor, in contrast to capital, is much more tied to places, it is highly differentiated according to place-specific histories, social experiences, cultural contexts, and such. Yet, labor, and people more generally, are moving globally in ever greater volumes. Some of these international migration patterns are long-standing, and precede globalization's ascendance in the last three decades.Others appear to be evolutionary, and derive their added complexity and unruliness from globalization's influences. Some others might even be regarded as direct consequences of globalization, or indirectly the result of social, economic and political upheavals and restructuring that has lead to this 'new age of migration'. One particular characteristic of this new-age, dynamic process is its 'unruliness', its unregulated, or difficult to regulate, nature, and its volatility and unpredictability. Another characteristic is its rapidly changing mix, with traditional distinctions between highly-skilled migration and lowskilled migration across borders becoming blurred as global mobility is accompanied by upward social mobility and increases in social, cultural and human capital stocks for many in both classes, such that middle-class increases are gathering pace.Attainment of the 'immigrant dream' is becoming more and more possible, despite the unruliness, the unpredictable and volatile times and the often desperate beginnings of the global journey. And, this chapter details this contemporary complexity, drawing distinctions between migration's unruliness that empowers people and brings positive returns and unruliness that endangers, disadvantages and often abuses and denies basic human rights to many of the millions involved in irregular flight. These latter 'unruly movers' seek the right to better livelihood opportunities by moving 'across borders', albeit without legal permission to enter or work in that 'other man's world'. Yet, anarchic unruliness at the borders, rising anti-immigrant national xenophobia, and unscrupulous migration facilitators-traffickers, smugglers, and criminal syndicates, and the like-only make their irregular world(s) more dangerous places and 'spaces'. © 2009 Nova Science Publishers, Inc.
