AB  - This paper focuses on the mobility of one specific group of the UK population: those people who were charged with a crime and detained in prison in the late 19th century. Police records for the Cumbrian (Westmorland) town of Kendal not only give details of the charges made in Kendal, but also list a large number of previous and subsequent offences including the place where the charge was made. Those who had no fixed address were often skilled and middle-aged, committed relatively minor offences but were quite harshly treated by the law. It seems likely that their high re-offence rate reflects the attitude of police to trampers rather than their predisposition to crime. Although those with no fixed address were more mobile than those with a fixed address, the pattern of their mobility was not atypical. 45.1% of those without a fixed address had moved only 31 miles (50 km) or less before re-offending and there is no significant difference in the length of time between the end of their sentence and another charge for the two groups. Those charged with crimes in Kendal rarely moved outside northern or midland England and most moved over relatively short distances within territory with which they were probably familiar. -from Author
